In the 2019-2020 school year, Physics and Calculus students had to adapt to new challenges to continue Passaic Valley‚Äôs Rube Goldberg Project Tradition. Nineteen students participated, creating ten unique Rube Goldberg machines. "The smaller number of students working on each project naturally caused the projects to be a bit smaller than usual, but in no way were they any less impressive," said Math Teacher, Ms. Quail. Read the full article on the Passaic Valley Rube Goldberg projects of 2020 in the Valley Echo, found on our district website.

https://www.pvhs.k12.nj.us/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=4&ModuleInstanceID=35&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=3559&PageID=1

shared_text:
Erin Mary is with Meredith McNeill at Passaic Valley Regional High School.
August 19 at 9:43 PM ¬∑ Instagram ¬∑

Due to the generous donations of the PV Class of 2008 and many other friends and families, a new bench and weeping cherry tree now grace the front walk of Passaic Valley HIgh School, in memory of Colin McNeill. The project was completed over several months, and this spring, thanks to the help of many, it was accomplished!

Sincere thanks to all who contributed to the fund! Your kindness did not go unnoticed, and the McNeill family will long remember your part in helping to support this collaborative effort. It helps us to know that Colin is remembered. We hope that you will stop and sit awhile!

Special thanks to:
Passaic Valley Class of 2008
Passaic Valley Administration
Board of Education
Pv Buildings and Grounds crew
Smitty's Landscaping
Dear Friends and Neighbors in the Community

The Little Mermaid Preview will premiere tonight at 6pm on the PV Vimeo and YouTube Channels!

Passaic Valley's Spring Musical this year has been delayed indefinitely due to the recent school closing. However, Passaic Valley‚Äôs Theatre Program continues to rehearse, while innovatively adhering to social distancing guidelines. Staff and cast members of this year's The Little Mermaid have turned to online conferencing technology to direct cast members in memorizing lines, choreographing musical numbers, and everything else a traditional production entails.

Technological issues involving computer lags and network connections presented challenges for the Theater Department early on, but cast and crew have worked through these issues. "We all know that we want this show to happen so we are all doing whatever we can to make this work‚Äù said Mr. Michael DeLuccia, Music Director. Read the full article written by Gabriella Gutierrez '22 in The Valley Echo.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bqCQaPdRBAg

Every year, new students join the Yearbook Class to work together, create a memorable theme and commemorate the graduating class. This year‚Äôs yearbook staff consists of 23 hard-working students along with Mrs. Cheryl Joseph and Mrs. Darcy Hall as their editors. This group is especially unique. When it came down to dedication and teamwork, they showed that they could still get things done, regardless of the new and sudden circumstances. The theme, ‚ÄúThrough Our Eyes‚Äù was created to reflect "what PV looks like through the eyes of the Class of 2020,‚Äù co-editor Gabriella Cordova shared. Thank you to the entire yearbook staff for going above and beyond to get things done! Read the full article written by Brianna Rodriguez'20 in the Valley Echo.
The expected ship date for yearbooks is mid June, as soon as we have a distribution date confirmed we will let all know.

post_text: Mr. Randall Sanders shares an amazing activity he is doing with his STEM classes. Before distance learning began, Sanders was in contact with a scientist at NASA. He is conducting hydroponic research to send the first fruiting plants to the space station with the ultimate goal of preparing them for interplanetary travel. He subsequently started an at home/school challenge to grow your own space peppers. The goal of the activity is to have the students grow their own peppers (the same ones they are testing in the NASA labs) using either hydroponics or geoponics. Once the peppers are mature, they will be sent to the University of New Mexico for capsaicin (the stuff that makes peppers hot) level testing. Unfortunately the peppers were not ready for the students to take home, when we left. But, Sanders has been caring for them in the meantime. Here are some pictures of the students growing space peppers, as well as a copy of the NASA mission patch. #NASA #Spacepeppers #PVSTEM #PVistheplacetobe

post_text: The Little Mermaid was supposed to debut on May 7, 2020. Given the circumstances of Covid-19 and how much time and effort the cast has put in we are hoping to figure out a way the show can go on. The cast has been preparing since January; Broadway stars and PV alumni led an intimate class right before auditions, the students also attended a Broadway workshop led by Beetlejuice Cast members in NYC, they completed classes at Montclair State University for a day, in acting, musical theater, stage combat and technical theater and just yesterday Zoomed with the original Chef Louis from the Little Mermaid on Broadway... not to mention the long hours of rehearsing they do everyday virtually! We will keep the community informed on our next decision regarding the date of the show. #pvistheplacetobe

Dual Enrollment Opportunity with Passaic County Community College

Students enrolled in Criminal Justice courses have an opportunity to earn college credit through our partnership with Passaic County Community College. The registration deadline for the Spring Semester has been extended to Thursday, April 30, 2020. The course fee is $180 (3-credit course) payable to PCCC (online payment option available). PCCC Criminal Justice courses include: Introduction to Law, Introduction to Criminal Justice, Juvenile Delinquency and Youth Crimes, and Investigative Functions.

Please contact Ms. Palmiere with any questions.

The Child Mind Institute recommends creating routines for students during this time of online learning. Building new routines and schedules could be helpful Hornets!
Be sure to take care of yourself mind and body.
shared_text:
Child Mind Institute
March 18 at 6:30 PM ¬∑

Every day the Child Mind Institute will publish a tip for supporting families through the coronavirus crisis.

Creating a secure home environment is important so that you and your children can deal with stress and uncertainty in a healthy way. Drawing from developmental psychology, here‚Äôs what parents can do:
- be predictable and consistent
- be responsive
- be nurturing and affectionate
- model calm reassurance and thoughtful problem solving

Visit our comprehensive coronavirus resource page: https://childmind.org/coronavirus
